Iterator in Python

“Iterator is an object used to iterate over data one element at a time.
It implements __iter__() and __next__() methods.
It helps in memory-efficient traversal because it doesn’t load all data at once.”
# Example of an iterator in Python
lst = [10, 20, 30]

it = iter(lst)   # convert to iterator

print(next(it))  # 10
print(next(it))  # 20
print(next(it))  # 30


What is Exception Handling?

Exception handling is used to handle runtime errors so that the program doesn’t crash and runs smoothly.
syntax:
try:
    # code that may raise an exception
except ExceptionType:
    # code to handle the exception
else:
    # code to execute if no exception occurs
finally:
    # code to execute regardless of exceptions
# Example of exception handling
try:
    x = 10 / 0  # This will raise ZeroDivisionError
except ZeroDivisionError:
    print("Cannot divide by zero!")
